							<a href="media/sea-2q12-olympic-gymnastics.swf" class="sea-award hidden" data-fancybox-group="sea-award" title="Service Excellence Award announcement, 2Q12: Gymnastics"><img src="img/sea/2q12-olympic-gymnastics-thumb.png" alt=""></a>
							<a href="media/sea-3q11-amazing-nature.swf" class="sea-award hidden" data-fancybox-group="sea-award" title="Service Excellence Award announcement, 3Q11: Amazing Nature"><img src="img/sea/3q11-amazing-nature-thumb.jpg" alt=""></a>
							<a href="media/sea-1q11-amazing-creations.swf" class="sea-award hidden" data-fancybox-group="sea-award" title="Service Excellence Award announcement, 1Q11: Amazing Creations"><img src="img/sea/1q11-amazing-creations-thumb.jpg" alt="">View Gallery</a>
						</div> <!-- /.thumb -->
						<div class="description col-md-9">
							<h3>Service Excellence Award announcements</h3>
							<p class="deck">The Challenge: Create a series of dynamic, engaging quarterly award announcements, with a different theme for each year.</p>
							<p>Similar to the Sell to Excel announcements in that there was a common theme, but different in that the theme, and hence the entire animation, changed each year. Themes included “Space” (stars, comets, planets, the sun), “Music” (classical, rock, jazz, blues), “Amazing” (based on a sales campaign slogan; amazing nature, amazing creations, amazing microscopic details, etc.), and my favorite, “Olympics” in 2012 (swimming, gymnastics, track & field, ice skating).</p>
							<p>In addition to the text and photo animation, these included <a href="img/sea/winners.jpg" class="fancybox">lists of the winners’ names</a>, grouped by organization, making them fairly content-heavy.</p>
						</div> <!-- /.description -->
					</div> <!--/.portfolio-item -->

					<div class="portfolio-item row">
						<div class="thumb col-md-3">
							<a href="media/marquee-voice-transformation-puzzle.swf" class="marquee" title="ATT.com Marquee: Voice Transformation (first version)"><img src="img/marquee/puzzle-thumb.jpg" alt="">View Animation</a>
						</div> <!-- /.thumb -->
						<div class="description col-md-9">
							<h3>ATT.com Marquee: Voice Transformation, Take 1</h3>
							<p class="deck">The Challenge: Develop an animated “marquee” graphic for ATT.com illustrating AT&T’s Voice Transformation initiative.</p>
							<p>Voice Transformation was all about integrating many of AT&T’s voice services under a common platform. The client suggested a theme of “putting together all the pieces of the puzzle,” which I took and ran with. I found a cool stock photo of a globe made up of puzzle pieces (AT&T loves globes!), and I had my concept. I put it together in a detailed <a href="img/marquee/puzzle-storyboard.jpg" class="fancybox" title="Voice Transformation marquee storyboard">detailed storyboard</a>, which the client signed off on immediately.</p>
						</div> <!-- /.description -->
					</div> <!--/.portfolio-item -->

					<div class="portfolio-item row">
						<div class="thumb col-md-3">
							<a href="media/marquee-voice-transformation-update.swf" class="marquee" title="ATT.com Marquee: Voice Transformation (update version)"><img src="img/marquee/update-thumb.jpg" alt="">View Animation</a>
						</div> <!-- /.thumb -->
						<div class="description col-md-9">
							<h3>ATT.com Marquee: Voice Transformation, Take 2</h3>
							<p class="deck">The Challenge: Update the previous Voice Transformation marquee to match a new sales infographic.</p>
							<p>About a year after the original Voice Transformation animation, the sales team put together a brochure and <a href="img/marquee/update-infographic.jpg" class="fancybox" title="New Voice Transformation infographic">snazzy infographic</a> explaining the initiative in greater detail. Transforming a strongly vertical infographic to fit a strongly horizontal marquee was a challenge, but I broke the original artwork down into <a href="img/marquee/update-storyboard.jpg" class="fancybox" title="Voice Transformation storyboard, revisited">a few “scenes” that fit the format</a>, imitating the infographic’s “arrow” element to ease the flow between the scenes, and animating the elements of each scene so that they “built” as they told the story.</p>
						</div> <!-- /.description -->
